frameDefinitions: In this frame an Agent continues to possess a Theme for a Duration of time. ''
The Authorities hold a Suspect under suspicion of having committed a crime (Charges).
A Cognizer applies oneself to commit a Pattern to memory, so that the Cognizer would recognize future examples of the Pattern or be able to reproduce it.
An Entity began its existence in the context of a location of Origin, which is a discourse-salient place, or culture.
A person (Speaker) expresses a Message or mental content, broadly understood, in a particular Manner.
In this frame a Container holds within its physical boundaries the Contents.
frameExamples: In her heart she must <t>retain</t> bitterness against those who had killed him.
The police <t>held</t> Mr. Smith in the slammer on charges of killing his lawyer.
A gaggle of students were frantically <t>memorizing</t> the answers out in the hall.
Obviously there are species that are <t>native</t> to China or used in Chinese Medicine that aren't used in Western or Cherokee Medicine and vice versa.

<fen>Speaker</fen>, the person who encodes the <fen>Message</fen>, occurs as the External Argument of all the verbs:
The <fen>Message</fen> is almost invariably expressed in an NP Object. (The only exceptions occur with the verb <t>express</t>, which is occasionally used with that-clause complements.)

For most of the words in this frame, some expression of <fen>Manner</fen> or <fen>Medium</fen> is obligatory. As in other frames, <fen>Manner</fen> expressions characterize the action (in this case, the speech act performed by the <fen>Speaker</fen>). However, a wide range of <fen>Manner</fen> expressions occurs in this frame, including the following types:

The <fen>Container</fen> is the physical object which holds within its boundaries the <fen>Contents</fen>
The <fen>Contents</fen> is the substance or objects contained within the physical bounds of the <fen>Container</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Container</fen> holds the <fen>Contents</fen>.
